# Security Review: `app.js`

The file is a 23-line minimal Express server with two endpoints (`/health`, `/users`) returning static data. There are no database queries, no user input handling, no auth, no file I/O, and no templating — so most traditional OWASP Top 10 classes (SQLi, XSS, SSRF, path traversal, deserialization, etc.) simply don't have surface area here. That said, there are several real hardening gaps worth addressing before this grows.

## Findings

### 1. No security headers (OWASP A05: Security Misconfiguration)
Express by default sets `X-Powered-By: Express` (information disclosure) and omits protective headers (`Content-Security-Policy`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `X-Content-Type-Options`, etc.).

**Fix:** use `helmet`.
```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet());
```

### 2. No rate limiting (OWASP A04: Insecure Design / DoS)
Both endpoints are unauthenticated and unthrottled — trivially abusable for DoS or scraping.

**Fix:**
```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100 }));
```

### 3. PII exposure without authentication (OWASP A01: Broken Access Control, A02: Cryptographic Failures)
`/users` returns email addresses to any unauthenticated caller. Even with mock data, this pattern will be copy-pasted.

**Fix:** gate behind auth middleware and return only fields the caller is authorized to see.
```js
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  res.json(users.map(u => ({ id: u.id, name: u.name })));
});
```

### 4. No CORS policy defined (OWASP A05)
Without explicit CORS config, behavior depends on deployment. Define it explicitly.
```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://trusted.example.com'], methods: ['GET'] }));
```

### 5. No HTTPS / TLS enforcement (OWASP A02)
`app.listen(3000)` serves plaintext HTTP. In production, terminate TLS at a proxy and redirect/force HTTPS:
```js
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  if (req.headers['x-forwarded-proto'] !== 'https') {
    return res.redirect('https://' + req.headers.host + req.url);
  }
  next();
});
```

### 6. No error handler / stack-trace leakage risk (OWASP A05, A09)
As the app grows, unhandled errors will surface stack traces to clients in development mode. Add a final error handler now:
```js
app.use((err, req, res, _next) => {
  console.error(err);
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' });
});
```

### 7. No request logging (OWASP A09: Security Logging & Monitoring Failures)
Nothing is logged beyond the startup line — you cannot investigate incidents.
```js
const morgan = require('morgan');
app.use(morgan('combined'));
```

### 8. No body-size limits / input parsing hardening (OWASP A04)
Not exploited today, but as soon as you add `app.use(express.json())`, set a cap:
```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '100kb' }));
```

### 9. Hard-coded port, no graceful shutdown (reliability, not strictly security, but relevant to availability — OWASP A04)
```js
const port = process.env.PORT || 3000;
const server = app.listen(port, () => console.log(`Server running on ${port}`));
process.on('SIGTERM', () => server.close());
```

